metadata.name: Sand Flow #5
metadata.description:
bstract generative art that simulates sandpainting.

"Sandpainting is the art of pouring coloured sands, and powdered pigments from minerals or crystals,
or pigments from other natural or synthetic sources onto a surface to make a fixed or unfixed sand painting.
Sand paintings have a long established cultural history in numerous social groupings around the globe."

Created from 100% code and math.

(Generation time is a little longer on this work (10-15 sec.), please be patient)

Hi-res. options:

- press 'i' to save .png with resolution = 1000px x 1000px
- press 't' to save .png with resolution = 2000px x 2000px
- press 's' to save .png with resolution = 6000px x 6000px

Created using p5js.

@Mutart, May, 2022.

metadata.name: The Tiny Seed #117
metadata.description:
Biological and inorganic matter often grow from a tiny seed. After leaving the seed, the trunk unfurls into an array of possibilities. After some time has passed, the seed is reborn.

Some seeds can take longer to grow than others. All seeds begin in the middle.

A couple resolutions: 256, 512, 1024, 2048 (larger is rarer)
All other parameters change the behavior, colorization, and animation of each piece.
This is a larger edition, since the parameter space is very wide.

Each piece is lightly interactive. During growth, more seeds can be added by clicking and drawing into untraversed territory.

When viewing the piece live, you can press the 's' key to take a capture. Captures may be scaled to any desired resolution using 'nearest-neighbor' scaling.

Made with p5.js, p5Fbo.js, and glsl

metadata.name: Sea of Shapes #112
metadata.description:
This program was inspired by the 2022 Genuary prompt "Make a sea of shapes." It is an abstract and geometric representation of water and waves. I tried to capture the many different possible states of a sea (windy, breezy, calm etc.) by changing parameters within the program for different outputs.

Press 'p' while on Live View to save a high quality (4000x4000) png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js

metadata.name: Mandatory Destiny #102
metadata.description:
"Mandatory Destiny" is the fifth collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

It is impossible for everyone to be equal. Too much of a person is defined by random chance. The country they were born in, the financial situation of their family, even their genetics. If someone was unlucky and has low natural IQ, they can't change it. And it affects their life significantly. If someone was born in a poor country or family, it might be extremely harder to get a good education, and later, a well-paying job. Some people are fortunate enough to get a headstart, while others aren't so lucky.

The only way for everyone to be truly equal would be identical starting conditions, and that's utterly impossible to achieve.

metadata.name: contrapuntos #183
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Impending Cloths #58
metadata.description:
IC makes use of fabric's potential for contrasts.
The same piece of cloth can seem to be falling, perfectly still and ready to be blown away, all at the same time.
It can look "very digital" while also achieving a high degree of texture. And so on, and so forth. Contrast and potential.
Also, "h" can be pressed to download in high resolution, although it may take up to a minute.

metadata.name: Visa to the stars #80
metadata.description:
Generative space scenes with an illustrative look.

Use the capture functions to export in big after opening it in its own window, the artwork is full of details.

Press SPACE to show/hide the menu

Control the camera and explore the scene with :
- Mouse Left : Rotate
- Mouse Right : Pan
- Mouse Middle : Zoom

I wrote an article about the project, with a technical breakdown of the piece at https://ulucode.com/wp/visa-to-the-stars/


Decent GPU REQUIRED, you can tune the performances with the "Quality" setting in the menu.
Better performances with Chrome.

Keyboard shortcuts:
SPACE : show/hide menu
A : toggle anti-aliasing
C : take a capture of the ccurrently selected resolution
R : reset camera position/orientation
S : display stats
P : pause animation

metadata.name: Generational Differences #107
metadata.description:
Based on 1-dimensional cellular automata, different pleasing patterns are produced by each generation changing the rules for the next one. Each token will produce a unique sequence of patterns, like a slideshow of mosaics. Transitions may be subtle or very drastical, since a small change on the rules has a huge effect.
Best enjoyed on fullscreen

Click anywhere on the canvas to stop/resume the creation of new generations.
Press s to download at the current resolution

Original minters will get 50% of the royalties

metadata.name: On the sea, I ... #8
metadata.description:
Generative painting based on churning waves with floating buoys. Represented in three different media.

Features:
- Three drawing styles: "watercolor" 70%, "brush" 30%, or "block" 70%
- Warm white or blue waves
- Variable border and column sizes
- Number of columns
- Calm waves at the edges or center
- Color 80% or red 20% buoys
- Buoy drawing style, "watercolor" or "brush"

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ‚Äôp‚Äô to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.
